<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5196&amp;p=54697#p54697"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Do you think it could mix sound like the GBA can (by mapping WRAM to $8000-$bfff) ?<br /></div><br />Yes, you could map WRAM to $8000+ and mix samples there.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Oh this is GREAT ! The MMC5 can play true samples without wasting all the CPU time !! ... A problem is that the rate at which the samples are read isn't doccumented.<br /></div><br />I don't think you understand.  The MMC5 can't initiate reads like 2A03  DMC. The timing is still controlled by your software.  Your code would do something like this-<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">wait for N cycles<br />read from $8001<br />wait for N cycles<br />read from $8002<br />...<br /></div><br />So you see, it's almost entirely useless.  You can't have any code running in 8000-BFFF (MMC5 plays ANYTHING read by the CPU), all it does is save you from doing a STA $5011.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4">loopy</a> — Mon Jan 04, 2010 6:47 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
